# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1924-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] The **1924 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 42nd season.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] The team finished first in the National League with a record of 93–60, winning the NL pennant for a record fourth consecutive season, a record that still stands today.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] They went on to the World Series, losing to the Washington Senators in seven games.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] In the final series of the 1924 season, the Giants were playing the Philadelphia Phillies at the Polo Grounds and battling for the pennant with the Robins.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] Giants outfielder Jimmy O'Connell offered Phillies shortstop Heinie Sand $500 to throw the games.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] Sand rejected the bribe and reported it to Phillies manager Art Fletcher.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] It eventually led to the lifetime suspension of O'Connell and Giants coach Cozy Dolan by Commissioner Landis, although future-Hall of Famers Frankie Frisch, George Kelly, and Ross Youngs were also implicated.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] October 4, 1924, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] October 5, 1924, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] October 9, 1924, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:1924-new-york-giants-season/1924-new-york-giants-season] October 10, 1924, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
